# Example .env Configuration

## Mock Mode Setup (No Database)
```
DB_MODE=mock
STORAGE_MODE=filesystem
JWT_SECRET=your-super-secret-jwt-key-123456
PORT=5000
```

## Database Mode Setup (Default)
```
DB_MODE=database
STORAGE_MODE=database
DB_URL=mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster.mongodb.net/blogapp
JWT_SECRET=your-super-secret-jwt-key-123456
PORT=5000
```

## Hybrid Mode 1 (Mock Auth + Real Database Articles)
```
DB_MODE=mock
STORAGE_MODE=database
DB_URL=mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster.mongodb.net/blogapp
JWT_SECRET=your-super-secret-jwt-key-123456
PORT=5000
```

## Hybrid Mode 2 (Real Auth + File System Articles)
```
DB_MODE=database
STORAGE_MODE=filesystem
DB_URL=mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster.mongodb.net/blogapp
JWT_SECRET=your-super-secret-jwt-key-123456
PORT=5000
```

## Configuration Explanation

### DB_MODE
- `mock` - Use pre-defined mock credentials for authentication
- `database` - Use MongoDB database for authentication (requires DB_URL)

### STORAGE_MODE
- `filesystem` - Store articles in JSON files (backend/data/)
- `database` - Store articles in MongoDB (requires DB_URL)

### JWT_SECRET
- Secret key for signing JWT tokens
- Keep it secure and change in production

### DB_URL
- MongoDB connection string
- Only required if DB_MODE=database or STORAGE_MODE=database

### PORT
- Server port (default: 5000)

## Mock Credentials Reference

When using DB_MODE=mock, use these credentials:

**Users:**
- user@example.com / user123
- jane.user@example.com / user123

**Authors:**
- author@example.com / author123
- bob.author@example.com / author123

**Admin:**
- admin@example.com / admin123
